Maxilliped (
<figureCitation box="[337,417,1537,1562]" captionStart="FIGURE 39" captionStartId="71.[151,250,1900,1922]" captionTargetBox="[167,1415,193,1879]" captionTargetId="figure@71.[167,1419,193,1879]" captionTargetPageId="71" captionText="FIGURE 39. Bradycalanus abyssicolus n. sp. female: A, mandibular gnathobase; B, maxillule (B 1 = basal endite 1, C = coxal endite); C, coxal endite (C) and basal endite 1 (B 1) of maxillule; D, maxilla; E, detail of vestigial coxal epipodite; F, detail of endopod of maxilla; G, maxilliped. Scale bars represent 1.0 mm on figures D, G; 0.1 mm on remaining figures. Illustrated specimen from ANDEEP II, ANTXIX / 4, Stn 135 - 4." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/293518/files/figure.png" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Fig. 39</figureCitation>
G) second most proximal seta on endopod segments 3–5 one third length of longest seta.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="72.[151,1437,1393,1994]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
Leg 1 (
<figureCitation box="[284,368,1573,1598]" captionStart="FIGURE 37" captionStartId="69.[151,250,1885,1907]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1863]" captionTargetId="figure@69.[151,1436,193,1863]" captionTargetPageId="69" captionText="FIGURE 37. Bradycalanus abyssicolus n. sp. female: A, dorsal view; B, lateral view; C, lateral view of anterior head; D, lateral view of posterior pedigerous somite 5; E, lateral view of genital double-somite; F, posterior view of leg 1. Scale bars represent 1.0 mm on figures A, B, E, F; 0.1 mm on remaining figures. Illustrated specimen from ANDEEP II, ANTXIX / 4, Stn 135 - 4." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/293516/files/figure.png" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
F) exopod segment 3 elongate and narrow, nearly 5 times as long as maximum width; distal border of endopod segment 1 extends to distal border of exopod segment 1; exopod outer spines: on segment 1 extends one third distance to outer spine on segment 2; on segment 2 extends about one third distance to proximal outer spine on segment 3; segment 3 proximal spine extends half distance to outer distal spine.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="72.[151,1437,1393,1994]" box="[199,380,1717,1742]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Male. Unknown</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="72" pageNumber="73" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="72.[151,1437,1393,1994]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1753,1778]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name is derived from the Latin words 
<emphasis box="[908,995,1753,1777]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">abyssus</emphasis>
= ‘deep sea’ and 
<emphasis box="[1194,1253,1753,1777]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">colus</emphasis>
= ‘dwelling in’, gender masculine. This name refers to the discovery of this species at depths greater than 
<quantity box="[1155,1243,1790,1814]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" unit="m" value="4000.0">4000 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="72" pageNumber="73" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="72.[151,1437,1393,1994]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1825,1850]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Distribution.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[362,656,1825,1849]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Megacalanidae" genus="Bradycalanus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Calanoida" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="abyssicolus" status="n.sp.">
<emphasis box="[362,656,1825,1849]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Bradycalanus abyssicolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[667,719,1826,1849]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" rank="species">n.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is an abyssopelagic species living at depths&gt; 
<quantity box="[1267,1358,1826,1850]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" unit="m" value="4000.0">4000 m</quantity>
. It has been found in 
<collectingCountry box="[312,464,1861,1886]" name="Argentina" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">the Argentine</collectingCountry>
Basin, the 
<collectingRegion box="[591,673,1861,1886]" country="Oman" name="Al Wusta" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Central</collectingRegion>
Weddell Sea and the equatorial Atlantic Ocean (
<figureCitation box="[1219,1302,1861,1886]" captionStart="FIGURE 29" captionStartId="58.[151,250,1060,1082]" captionTargetBox="[179,1407,395,1008]" captionTargetId="figure@58.[151,1436,365,1042]" captionTargetPageId="58" captionText="FIGURE 29. Distribution of Bradycalanus species: open square = Bradycalanus enormis; filled square = Br. typicus; open triangle = Br. gigas; open circle = Br. abyssicolus n. sp.." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/293509/files/figure.png" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
, 
<tableCitation box="[1313,1395,1861,1886]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="6.[121,197,553,573]" captionTargetBox="[119,1865,736,1449]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="TABLE 1. Station data and capture circumstances for Megacalanidae newly studied here. BN = Benthic net; EBS-S = Epibenthic Sledge — supranet (top); IKMT = Isaacs-Kidd Midwater Trawl; = Multinet; MOC 10 = 10 m 2 MOCNESS net; MOC 1 = 1 m 2 MOCNESS net; mwo = metres of wire out; N 100 = 1 m diameter net with stramin mesh (Sewell 1935); N 200 = 2 m diameter" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF2AD8F7BB7CFFBD01506504F8E5003D" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" tableUuid="DF2AD8F7BB7CFFBD01506504F8E5003D">Table 1</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="72.[151,1437,1393,1994]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,451,1897,1922]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Species comparisons.</emphasis>
This species is easily distinguished from other described 
<taxonomicName box="[1101,1256,1897,1921]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Megacalanidae" genus="Bradycalanus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Calanoida" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1101,1256,1897,1921]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Bradycalanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as it is the only species that has a crested head, a reduced number of setae on the coxal endite of the maxillule, and a narrow leg 1 exopod, in particular, exopod segment 3 which is nearly 5 times its maximum width (
<tableCitation box="[1106,1193,1969,1994]" captionStart="TABLE 8" captionStartId="65.[125,198,1141,1163]" captionText="TABLE 8. Comparison of key differences among Bradycalanus species. A 1 = antennule; A 2 = antenna; Mx 1 = maxillule; C = coxal endite; P 1, 5 = leg 1, 5; Re 1 — 3 = exopod segments 1 — 3; Re I— III = exopod ancestral segments I— III; Ri 1, 3 = endopod segments 1, 3." pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Table 8</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
